itizen anger. But as When Blame Backfires demonstrates, that is not always the case. What Baylouny exposes, instead, is that many of the problems that might be associated with refugees are in fact endemic to the normal routine of citizens' lives. The refugee crisis exacerbated an already-dire situation rather than creating it, and Jordanians and Lebanese started to protest not only against the presence of refugees but against the incompetence and corruption of their own governments as well.From small-scale protests about goods and public services, citizens progressed to organized and formal national movements calling for economic change and rights to public services not previously provided. This dramatic shift in protest and political discontent was, Baylouny shows, the direct result of the arrival of Syrian refugees.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPolitical refugeeszJordan x Economic conditionsy21st century. 0aPolitical refugeeszJordanxPublic opinion. 0aPolitical refugeeszLebanon x Economic conditionsy21st century. 0aPolitical refugeeszLebanonxPublic opinion. 0aPolitical refugeeszSyriaxEconomic conditionsy21st century. 0aPolitical refugeeszSyriaxPublic opinion. 4aHumanities & Human Rights. 4aMiddle East Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  agovernment corruption, economic greivances.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBo